 ## 3. Target Product And Proof Profile
 
 ### 3.1 Target end state
 
 The end state joins one operating fabric rather than a set of adjacent apps:
 
 ```text
 Product and collaboration
   Goal Space + Hypervisor clients
   Home / Systems / Projects / Applications / Work
   owner, substrate, tool, and extension surfaces
 
 Shared pursuit
   OutcomeRoom / CollaborativeWorkGraph
   GoalRunProfile -> GoalRun -> GoalKernel
   admitted participants, offers, claims, attempts, findings, verification
 
 Governed execution
   Hypervisor Core + Rust Hypervisor Daemon
   RuntimeToolContract / HarnessProfile / SkillManifest / WorkflowTemplate
   Type 1, Type 2, and Type 3 postures over one control plane
 
 Authority, truth, memory, and evidence
   local/domain policy + wallet.network
   Agentgres operations, heads, roots, receipts, projections, replay
   institutional learning boundary + policy-bound MemorySpace
 
 Distribution, federation, and settlement
   one logical bounded DAS across admitted nodes
   AIIP only across separately sovereign systems accepting exact terms
   optional IOI Network services and sparse L1 commitments
 ```
 
 The five core workspaces are `Home`, `Systems`, `Projects`, `Applications`,
 and `Work`. The enduring owner applications are `Studio`, `Automations`,
 `Ontology`, `Data`, `Governance`, `Provenance`, `Evaluations`, `Improvement`,
 `Foundry`, `Packages`, `Developer Workspace`, and `Developer Console`.
 `Environments` and `Operations` are substrate applications.
 `Embodied Systems` is conditional and remains unavailable until its contracts,
 route, projection, and implementation are real.
 
 ### 3.2 Selected first deployment profile
 
 | Dimension | Frozen first-proof choice |
 | --- | --- |
 | Institution | One OutcomeRoom-backed bounded software-change System |
 | Deployment | One node, one active writer, one failure domain |
 | Authority | One declared `single_authority` profile with protected amendment |
 | Admission | One hosted room-admission domain |
 | Repository | One sandboxed repository and protected sandbox branch |
 | Pursuit | One immutable GoalRunProfile, one durable GoalRun, optional directed workflow |
 | Contributors | Human sponsor, disclosed first-party workers, one untrusted local agent |
 | Verification | One deterministic independent verifier plus retained negative/challenged attempts |
 | Consequential effect | Apply or refuse one exact verified repository change |
 | Identity | Deployment-local identity and locally permitted nonportable exact-effect authority; provider-neutral account/session plus passkey-capable step-up is the ordered managed-optionality overlay |
 | Truth | Agentgres-backed operations, heads, receipts, replay, and export |
 | Learning | Private correction/eval canary and two substitutable eligible model routes |
 | Billing | Measured internal cost only |
 | Network | No AIIP, public payment, IOI enrollment, L1, or native asset dependency |
 | Embodiment | None |
 
 ### 3.3 Visible terminal journey
 
 A person who did not build IOI must be able to:
 
 1. obtain a supported release and verify its signer, digest, manifest, and
    revocation posture without an implicit network fallback;
 2. preview install paths, endpoints, custody, supervisor behavior, and egress,
    then explicitly authorize installation;
 3. bootstrap deployment-local identity and locally permitted authority, start
    the declared local core, observe bounded component readiness, and inspect
    shared status, doctor, and logs through a supported client;
 4. continue through that local identity or, only for the managed-optionality
    overlay, an eligible identity provider or passkey;
 5. choose a bounded software-change template;
 6. describe the goal, repository, constraints, budget, verification, data, and
    authority posture in ordinary product language;
 7. review any evidence-bearing project-discovery proposal, select an exact
    candidate and override set, and explicitly create the resulting Project or
    development-environment recipe;
 8. validate, preview, and simulate the compiled package/genesis proposal;
 9. approve genesis and inspect the stable System;
 10. start or admit the GoalRun in its OutcomeRoom-backed Work context;
 11. pair one local agent through an expiring, origin-bound, proposal-only flow;
 12. observe frontier items, claims, attempts, findings, verification, blockers,
    costs, and course corrections;
 13. replace a Session, worker, or eligible model route without replacing the
    GoalRun;
 14. review the exact proposed repository effect and its evidence;
 15. unlock a scoped grant with a passkey when the selected authority profile
     requires it;
 16. let the daemon revalidate policy, authority, revocation, information-flow
     labels, writer fence, target head, idempotency, and effect hash at the final
     invoker;
 17. execute once or refuse with zero unauthorized or duplicate effect;
 18. inspect the diff, tests, route, costs, learning eligibility, receipts,
     state root, and accepted OutcomeDelta;
 19. export and verify the evidence offline;
 20. disable the incumbent provider and continue above the frozen model-exit
     threshold using institution-controlled eligible state;
 21. exercise signed update, rollback/recall, backup, staged restore,
     route-binding change, cleanup reconciliation, revocation, archive,
     stop/uninstall without implicit wipe, and retirement.
 
 The journey fails if any transition requires an unavailable privileged script,
 hidden database edit, copied bearer authority, fabricated projection, prompt-
 only state mutation, or manual reconstruction of the proof chain.
 
