 ### M2 — Deployment, Membership, Fencing, And Transition Truth
 
 Canonical build step: 2.
 
 Prerequisites: verified M1.
 
 Objective: separate desired topology from observed membership and make every
 writer/effect transition reconstructable and fenced.
 
 Required work:
 
 - `M2.1` admit deployment, durability, failure-domain, node-role, and failover
   profiles separately from node identity;
 - `M2.2` implement membership proposal/admission, role lease, readiness,
   catch-up, watermark, state-root, drain, removal, and degraded-state records;
 - `M2.3` bind one single-node active-writer epoch and transition commitment to
   the System;
 - `M2.4` make active resource fences daemon-generated and impossible for a
   caller to author;
 - `M2.5` bind selected final invokers to current membership, epoch, resource,
   grant, and effect facts;
 - `M2.6` preserve lost/ambiguous suffix and reconciliation obligations rather
   than inferring success from timeout or restore;
 - `M2.7` rebuild desired and observed projections from Agentgres-backed truth;
 - `M2.8` implement immutable route bindings whose ownership, TLS, target,
   observed state, activation head, renewal, detach, and drift remain separate
   from environment ports;
 - `M2.9` implement manifest-complete environment backups and staged restore
   through `HypervisorChangePlan`, including aggregate read-only target preflight,
   apply-time revalidation, per-secret disposition, full-byte verification, and
   destination-local credential re-resolution;
 - `M2.10` make activation a forward-only compare-and-swap and persist resource
   cleanup obligations across parent deletion, provider loss, rollback,
   supersession, and ambiguous effects.
 
 Exit proof:
 
 - a stale, foreign, deposed, malformed, or caller-authored writer context
   reaches zero effectors;
 - restart repairs projections without hiding fork, gap, tamper, collision, or
   unreadable legacy state;
 - node placement cannot widen authority, finality, or System identity;
 - desired topology and observed readiness remain visibly distinct; and
 - incomplete backup manifests, stale restore preflights, failed or superseded
